<section xml:id="sec-derivApp-curve1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Curve Sketching Part 1</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Determine where a function is increasing or decreasing using the sign of <m>f'(x)</m>.</li>
      <li>Use the First Derivative Test to classify critical points as local maxima, local minima, or neither.</li>
      <li>Determine concavity using the sign of <m>f''(x)</m> and identify inflection points.</li>
      <li>Combine derivative information with intercepts and asymptotes to sketch a reasonable graph.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>


<warning xml:id="wrn-curve1-prereq">
  <title>Prerequisite Review</title>

<p>A key skill needed for curve sketching is the ability to solve equations and inequalities involving derivatives.
  If you feel a bit out of practice with your inequality solving techniques, it may be helpful
  to revisit those ideas before diving into the calculus.

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><xref ref="ssec-ineq-overview">Review section on inequalities</xref></p>
  </li>
</ul>

</p>
</warning>


  <p>
    Derivatives do more than provide slopes at individual points.
    They also reveal the overall shape of a graph.
    In this section, we build a toolkit for sketching the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m>
    by analyzing <m>f'(x)</m> and <m>f''(x)</m>.
    The goal is not a perfect drawing, but a reliable picture that captures the key features.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-increasing-decreasing">
    <title>Increasing and Decreasing</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-increasing-decreasing">
      <title>Increasing and Decreasing</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A function <m>f</m> is <term>increasing</term> on an interval <m>[a,b]</m> if
          <m>f(x_1)&lt;f(x_2)</m> whenever <m>x_1&lt;x_2</m> in <m>[a,b]</m>.
          A function <m>f</m> is <term>decreasing</term> on <m>[a,b]</m> if
          <m>f(x_1)&gt;f(x_2)</m> whenever <m>x_1&lt;x_2</m> in <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      The derivative provides an efficient test: the graph rises where slopes are positive
      and falls where slopes are negative.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-inc-dec">
      <title>Increasing/Decreasing Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be continuous on <m>[a,b]</m> and differentiable on <m>(a,b)</m>.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f'(x)&gt;0</m> for all <m>x\in(a,b)</m>, then <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>[a,b]</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f'(x)&lt;0</m> for all <m>x\in(a,b)</m>, then <m>f</m> is decreasing on <m>[a,b]</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Assume <m>f'(x)&gt;0</m> for all <m>x\in(a,b)</m>, and choose any <m>x_1&lt;x_2</m> in <m>[a,b]</m>.
          By the Mean Value Theorem, there exists <m>c\in(x_1,x_2)</m> such that
        </p>
        <me>
          f'(c)=\frac{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}{x_2-x_1}.
        </me>
        <p>
          Since <m>x_2-x_1&gt;0</m> and <m>f'(c)&gt;0</m>, we have <m>f(x_2)-f(x_1)&gt;0</m>, so <m>f(x_2)&gt;f(x_1)</m>.
          Therefore <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>[a,b]</m>. The decreasing case is similar.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex-inc-dec-poly">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x)=x^5-15x^3</m>.
        </p>
        <p>(a) Identify all critical points of <m>f</m> and determine where it is increasing and decreasing.</p> 
        <p>(b) Use your results from (a) to plot a sketch of the graph of <m>f</m>.</p>
        <p>(c) Use your sketch from (b) to classify the critical points as local maxima, minima, or neither. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution> <title>Video Solution</title>
      
      
        <p>
          Here is a video solution to this problem.
        </p>

          <p>
              <video youtube="eYcCeFBrLqc" width="90%">
              </video>
          </p>
      </solution>
      <solution> <title>Written Solution</title>
      
      
        <p>
          (a) Differentiate:
        </p>

        <me>
          f'(x)=5x^4-45x^2=5x^2(x^2-9)=5x^2(x-3)(x+3).
        </me>

        <p>
          The critical points occur where <m>f'(x)=0</m> (since it is never undefined), so <m>x=-3,0,3</m>.
        </p>
        <p>Since we will need to plot the graph, we should also compute the <m>y</m>-coordinates of the critical points:</p> 
        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
            f(-3) &amp; = &amp; (-3)^5-15(-3)^3  = 162\\
            f(0) &amp; = &amp; 0^5-15\cdot 0^3 = 0\\
            f(3) &amp; = &amp; 3^5-15\cdot 3^3 = -162
          \end{array}
        </me> 
      <p>Now we will use the test point method to determine where <m>f'(x) \gt 0</m> 
          (i.e., where the function is increasing) and where <m>f'(x) \lt 0</m> (i.e., where the function is decreasing).</p>

        <p> Choose test points in each of the intervals determined by the critical points: </p> 

        <me>
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
  \text{Interval} &amp; \text{Test Point} &amp; \text{Sign of } f'(x) \\ \hline
 (-\infty,-3) &amp; -4 &amp; (+)(-)(-)\to(+) \\ \hline
(-3,0) &amp; -1 &amp; (+)(-)(+)\to(-) \\ \hline
(0,3) &amp; 1 &amp; (+)(-)(+)\to(-) \\ \hline
(3,\infty) &amp; 4 &amp; (+)(+)(+)\to(+) \\ \hline
\end{array}
</me>

        
        <p><em>Remember:</em> That the value of the derivative at the test point is not important; only the sign matters.
          The sign of <m>f'(x)</m> is determined by the signs of the factors <m>5x^2</m>, <m>(x-3)</m>, and <m>(x+3)</m> (hence 
          the short-hand notation in the table above). </p> 
          
        <p>
          A sign chart is summarized below.
        </p>

        <me>
          \begin{array}{c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c}
          x &amp; -4 &amp; -3 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 \\ \hline
          f'(x) &amp; (+) &amp; 0 &amp; (-) &amp; 0 &amp; (-) &amp; 0 &amp; (+) \\ \hline
          f(x) &amp; \nearrow &amp; 162 &amp; \searrow &amp; 0 &amp; \searrow &amp; -162 &amp; \nearrow
          \end{array}
        </me>

        <p>(b) To sketch the graph we can first plot the critical points and then use the increasing/decreasing behavior to connect them. 
        </p> 

