    <p>
      A helpful way to connect this to derivatives is to think about slopes.
      When a function is concave up, its slopes tend to increase as <m>x</m> increases.
      When a function is concave down, its slopes tend to decrease.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-concavity-test">
      <title>Concavity Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be twice differentiable on an interval <m>(a,b)</m>.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f''(x)&gt;0</m> for all <m>x\in(a,b)</m>, then <m>f</m> is concave up on <m>(a,b)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f''(x)&lt;0</m> for all <m>x\in(a,b)</m>, then <m>f</m> is concave down on <m>(a,b)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f''(c)=0</m> and <m>f''</m> changes sign at <m>x=c</m>, then <m>(c,f(c))</m> is an inflection point.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Apply the Increasing/Decreasing Test to <m>g(x)=f'(x)</m>.
          If <m>g'(x)&gt;0</m>, then <m>g</m> is increasing.
          Since <m>g'(x)=(f'(x))'=f''(x)</m>, the condition <m>f''(x)&gt;0</m> means <m>f'(x)</m> is increasing,
          which corresponds to concave up behavior. The concave down case is similar,
          and the inflection point criterion follows from a sign change in <m>f''</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex-concavity-poly">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Continue with <m>f(x)=x^5-15x^3</m>. Find where the graph is concave up or concave down,
          and identify inflection points.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution> <title>Video Solution</title>
      
      
        <p>
          Here is a video solution to this problem.
        </p>

          <p>
              <video youtube="eYcCeFBrLqc" width="90%">
              </video>
          </p>
      </solution>
      <solution> <title>Written Solution</title>
        <p>
          We already computed <m>f'(x)=5x^4-45x^2</m>. Differentiate again:
        </p>

        <me>
          f''(x)=20x^3-90x=10x(2x^2-9).
        </me>

        <p>
          Candidate inflection points occur where <m>f''(x)=0</m> or where <m>f''(x)</m> is undefined (while <m>f</m> is defined). 
          However since <m>f''(x)</m> is defined for all real <m>x</m>, we only consider where <m>f''(x)=0</m>.
          So either
          <m>10x=0 \implies x=0</m> or <m>2x^2-9=0</m>, which gives <m>x=\pm\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{2}}</m>.
        </p>
        <p> Remember that <m>\sqrt{2}\approx 1.4</m> so the inflection points are approximately at <m>x=-2.1</m>, <m>x=0</m>, and <m>x=2.1</m>. </p> 

      <p>Now we will use the test point method to determine where <m>f''(x) \gt 0</m> 
          (i.e., where the function is concave up) and where <m>f''(x) \lt 0</m> (i.e., where the function is concave down).</p>

        <p> Choose test points in each of the intervals and check the sign of <m>f''(x)=(2x^2-9)</m>:  </p> 

        <me>
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
  \text{Interval} &amp; \text{Test Point} &amp; \text{Sign of } f''(x) \\ \hline
 (-\infty,-\tfrac{3}{\sqrt{2}}) &amp; -4 &amp; (-)(+) \to (-) \\ \hline
(-\tfrac{3}{\sqrt{2}},0) &amp; -1 &amp; (-)(-)\to(+) \\ \hline
(0,\tfrac{3}{\sqrt{2}}) &amp; 1 &amp; (+)(-)\to(-) \\ \hline
(\tfrac{3}{\sqrt{2}},\infty) &amp; 4 &amp; (+)(+)\to(+) \\ \hline
\end{array}
</me>

  <p>So therefore <m>f</m> is concave down on <m>(-\infty,-\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}}) \cup (0,\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}})</m>, 
    and concave up on <m>(-\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}},0) \cup (\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}},\infty)</m>.</p>

  <p>Because <m>f''</m> changes sign at each of the three candidates, there are inflection points at 
    <m>x=-\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}}</m>, <m>x=0</m>, and <m>x=\frac{3}{\sqrt{2}}</m>.</p>


      </solution>
    </example>

