        </p> 
        <me>
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
  \text{Interval} &amp; \text{Test Point} &amp; \text{Sign of } f'(x) \\ \hline
 (-\infty,-\frac{1}{2}) &amp; -1 &amp; \frac{(+)}{(-)(-)} \to (+) \\ \hline
(-\frac{1}{2},0) &amp; -\frac{1}{4} &amp; \frac{(-)}{(-)(-)} \to (-) \\ \hline
(0,1) &amp; \frac{1}{2} &amp; \frac{(-)}{(+)(-)} \to (+) \\ \hline
(1,\infty) &amp; 2 &amp; \frac{(-)}{(+)(+)} \to (-) \\ \hline
\end{array}
</me>
  <p>
    So <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>(-\infty,-\frac{1}{2}) \cup (0,1)</m> and decreasing on <m>(-\frac{1}{2},0) \cup (1,\infty)</m>.
  </p>
  <p>(c) To determine concavity, we compute the second derivative. We can use the quotient rule again, or we can differentiate the expression we found for <m>f'(x)</m>.
    We will use the quotient rule on the expression for <m>f'(x)</m> to practice that skill again. To make the derivative a bit easier 
    to compute, we will first write 
  </p>
  <me> 
    f'(x) = \dfrac{-4x-2}{3x^{1/3}(x-1)^3} = \dfrac{-2}{3}\cdot \dfrac{2x^{2/3}+x^{-1/3}}{(x-1)^3} 
  </me>
  <p>Taking the derivative, we get:</p>
  <me>
  \begin{array}{rcl}
    f''(x) &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{(2x^{2/3}+x^{-1/3})'(x-1)^3 - (2x^{2/3}+x^{-1/3})((x-1)^3)'}{(x-1)^6} \\
    &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{(\frac{4}{3}x^{-1/3}-\frac{1}{3}x^{-4/3})(x-1)^3 - (2x^{2/3}+x^{-1/3})(3(x-1)^2)}{(x-1)^6} \\
    &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{(\frac{4}{3}x^{-1/3}-\frac{1}{3}x^{-4/3})(x-1) - (2x^{2/3}+x^{-1/3})(3)}{(x-1)^4} \\
    &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{\frac{4}{3}x^{-1/3}(x-1) -\frac{1}{3}x^{-4/3}(x-1) - 6x^{2/3} - 3x^{-1/3}}{(x-1)^4} \\
    &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{\frac{4}{3}x^{-1/3}(x-1) -\frac{1}{3}x^{-4/3}(x-1) - 6x^{2/3} - 3x^{-1/3}}{(x-1)^4} \cdot \frac{3x^{4/3}}{3x^{4/3}} \\
    &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{4x(x-1) - (x-1) - 18x^2 - 9x}{3x^{4/3}(x-1)^4} \\
    &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{-14x^2 -14x +1}{3x^{4/3}(x-1)^4} \\
      &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{2}{9} \cdot \dfrac{14x^2 + 14x -1}{x^{4/3}(x-1)^4}
\end{array}
  </me>
  <p>
    Candidate inflection points occur where <m>f''(x)=0</m> or where <m>f''(x)</m> is undefined (while <m>f</m> is defined). 
    Since <m>f''(x)</m> is undefined at <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=1</m>, we know <m>x=0</m> is a possible inflection point (but <m>x=1</m> is not, since <m>f</m> is undefined there). 
  </p>
  <p> We also set the numerator equal to zero and solve for <m>x</m> to find other candidates: </p>
  <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
14x^2 + 14x -1 &amp; = &amp; 0 \\
x &amp; = &amp; \frac{-14 \pm \sqrt{14^2 - 4\cdot 14 \cdot (-1)}}{2\cdot 14} \\
&amp; = &amp; \frac{-14 \pm \sqrt{196 + 56}}{28} \\
&amp; = &amp; \frac{-14 \pm \sqrt{252}}{28} \\
&amp; = &amp; \frac{-14 \pm 6\sqrt{7}}{28} \\
&amp; = &amp; \frac{-1}{2} \pm \frac{3\sqrt{7}}{14}
\end{array}
  </me>
  <p>Since <m>\frac{3\sqrt{7}}{14} \approx 0.5</m>, the candidates from the numerator are approximately at <m>x=-1</m> and <m>x=0</m>. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
-->


        <example xml:id="ex-curvesketch-rational">
      <title>Longer Example</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the function 
          <m>f(x)=x+\dfrac{1}{x+1}-\dfrac{3}{2}</m>.
        </p> 
        <p>(a) Identify intercepts, vertical asymptotes, and horizontal asymptotes of the graph of <m>f</m>.</p>
        <p>(b) Locate critical points and intervals of increase/decrease.</p>
        <p>(c) Determine concavity and inflection points.</p>
        <p>(d) Use your results from (a)-(c) to sketch the graph of <m>f</m>.</p> 
      </statement>

      <solution> <title>Video Solution</title>
      
      
        <p>
          Here is a video solution to this problem.
        </p>

          <p>
              <video youtube="eYcCeFBrLqc" width="90%">
              </video>
          </p>
      </solution>

      <solution>
        <title>Written Solution</title>
        <p>(a) The y-intercept occurs at <m>f(0)=\frac{-1}{2}</m>. Setting <m>f(x)=0</m> and solving for <m>x</m>, we find:
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
              0 &amp; = &amp; x+\dfrac{1}{x+1}-\dfrac{3}{2} \\
              2(x+1) \left(0) &amp; = &amp;2(x+1) ( x+\dfrac{1}{x+1} - \dfrac{3}{2} ) \\
              0 &amp; = &amp; 2x(x+1) + 2 - 3(x+1) \\
              0 &amp; = &amp; 2x^2 + 2x + 2 - 3x - 3 \\
              0 &amp; = &amp; 2x^2 - x - 1 \\
              0 &amp; = &amp; (2x+1)(x-1)
              \end{array}
          </me>
            so the x-intercepts are at <m>x=-\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>x=1</m>. </p> 
            <p>  There is a vertical asymptote at <m>x=-1</m> since the denominator of the rational part is zero there and the numerator is not. 
          To find horizontal asymptotes, we compute limits as <m>x\to\pm\infty</m>. 
          We can use dominant term analysis to find that
          <me>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\pm\infty} f(x) \approx \lim_{x\to\pm\infty} x = \pm\infty</me>
          so there are no horizontal asymptotes.
            </p>
            <p>(b) To find critical points, we first compute the derivative: </p>
        <me>
          f'(x) = 1 - \dfrac{1}{(x+1)^2} = \dfrac{(x+1)^2 - 1}{(x+1)^2} = \dfrac{x^2 + 2x}{(x+1)^2}.
        </me> 
        <p>
          The critical points occur where <m>f'(x)=0</m> or where <m>f'(x)</m> is undefined (while <m>f</m> is defined). 
          Since <m>f'(x)</m> only undefined when <m>x=-1</m> (since the denominator is zero there), and <m>f</m> is undefined at <m>x=-1</m>, 
          we only consider where <m>f'(x)=0</m>.
          Setting the derivative equal to zero and solving for <m>x</m>, we find:
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
              0 &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{x^2 + 2x}{(x+1)^2} \\
              0 &amp; = &amp; x^2+2x \\
              0 &amp; = &amp; x(x+2)
              \end{array}
          </me>
          so the critical points are at <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=-2</m>.            
        </p>
        <p> 
          To determine where <m>f</m> is increasing or decreasing, we can use the test point method to check the sign of <m>f'(x)</m> in each
          interval determined by the critical points and vertical asymptote:
        </p> 
        <me>
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
  \text{Interval} &amp; \text{Test Point} &amp; \text{Sign of } f'(x) \\ \hline
 (-\infty,-2) &amp; -3 &amp; \dfrac{(-)(-)}{(+)} \to (+) \\ \hline
(-2,-1) &amp; -\frac{3}{2} &amp; \dfrac{(-)(+)}{(+)} \to (-) \\ \hline
(-1,0) &amp; -\frac{1}{2} &amp; \dfrac{(-)(+)}{(+)} \to (-) \\ \hline
(0,\infty) &amp; 1 &amp; \dfrac{(+)(+)}{(+)} \to (+)
\end{array}
</me>
<p>  So <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>(-\infty,-2) \cup (0,\infty)</m> and decreasing on <m>(-2,-1) \cup (-1,0)</m>. </p>
<p>(c) To determine concavity, we compute the second derivative: </p>
<me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
f''(x) &amp; = &amp; \left(1 - \dfrac{1}{(x+1)^2}\right)' \\
&amp; = &amp; 0 - \dfrac{2}{(x+1)^3}
\end{array}
</me>
<p>
Candidate inflection points occur where <m>f''(x)=0</m> or where <m>f''(x)</m> is undefined (while <m>f</m> is defined). 
Since <m>f''(x)</m> is undefined at <m>x=-1</m>, we do not consider that point since <m>f</m> is also undefined there. 
Setting the second derivative equal to zero and solving for <m>x</m>, we find:
<me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
0 &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2}{(x+1)^3} \\
0 &amp; = &amp; -2
\end{array}
</me>
<p> 
Since there is no value of <m>x</m> that makes <m>f''(x)=0</m>, there are no inflection points.
</p>
<p>  To determine where <m>f</m> is concave up or concave down, we can use the test point method to check the sign of <m>f''(x)</m> in each
          interval determined by the vertical asymptote:
</p>
<me>
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
  \text{Interval} &amp; \text{Test Point} &amp; \text{Sign of } f''(x) \\ \hline
 (-\infty,-1) &amp; -2 &amp; \dfrac{-2}{(-)} \to (+) \\ \hline
(-1,\infty) &amp; 0 &amp; \dfrac{-2}{(+)} \to (-) \\ \hline 
\end{array}
</me>
<p>
So <m>f</m> is concave up on <m>(-\infty,-1)</m> and concave down on <m>(-1,\infty)</m>.
</p>
<p>(d) We can now combine all of this information to sketch the graph of <m>f</m>.
</p> 

<figure xml:id="fig-inc-dec-concavity-intervals-2">
  <caption>
    A sign chart showing intervals of increase, decrease, and concavity.
    The function is increasing and concave down on the left interval,
    decreasing and concave down on the next interval,
    decreasing and concave up after the inflection point,
    and increasing on the rightmost interval.
  </caption>

  <shortdescription>
    A coordinate plane divided by a vertical dashed line marking a critical or inflection value.
    The leftmost region is shaded and labeled “INC, CON DOWN.”
    The next region is labeled “DEC.”
    To the right of the dashed line the region is labeled “DEC, CON UP.”
    The far right region is labeled “INC.”
    Several points are marked on the graph to indicate function values in different intervals.
  </shortdescription>

  <image source="images/curvePlot3.PNG" width="85%"/>
</figure>


        </solution>

        </example>




